name: percent
description: Parts per hundred. This is one of the few symbols which can be used with multiple unit classes. It can be used with each class that represent a ratio of like quantities (e.g., mass per mass).

name: part per thousand
description: A ratio of values divided by 1000 where the original values were in the same units.

name: part per million
description: A ratio of values divided by 1E6 where the original values were in the same units.

name: euclid
description: A dimensionless unit of proportion, named after the Greek mathematician, Euclid. It represents the SI implied unit of "1" which is sometimes called a "dimensionless derived unit".

name: byte
description: 8 bit byte.

name: bit
description: A bit (a contraction of binary digit) is the basic unit of information in computing and telecommunications. A bit can have only two values: either 1 or 0.

name: percent [mass basis]
description: The percent of mass relative to mass. That is, mass divided by mass divided 100 where the original mass values were in the same units.

name: part per million [mass basis]
description: The parts per million of mass relative to mass. That is, mass divided by mass divided by 1E6 where the original mass values were in the same units.

name: percent [volume basis]
description: The percent of volume relative to volume That is, volume divided by volume divided by 100 where the original volume values were in the same units.

name: part per million [volume basis]
description: The parts per million of volume relative to volume That is, volume divided by volume divided by 1E6 where the original volume values were in the same units.

name: femtoeuclid

description: Parts per thousand million.

name: picoeuclid

name: teraeuclid

name: microeuclid
description: Parts per million.

name: kibibyte
description: 1024 bytes.

name: mebibyte
description: 1048576 bytes. Commonly called a megabyte but mega refers to powers of ten rather than powers of two.

capture unit
description: The macroscopic capture cross section is the sum of all the various weighted elemental capture cross sections. The are "1E-3 cm2/cm3" often referred to as capture unit (c.u.) or sigma unit (s.u.). (Adapted from Ransom, Robert C," Practical Formation Evaluation", New York: J Wiley, 1995.)

name: curie
description: The Curie (symbol Ci) is a non-SI unit of radioactivity, named after Marie and Pierre Curie. It is defined as 3.7E10 decays per second. The SI derived unit of radioactivity is the becquerel (Bq), which equates to one decay per second.

name: baud
description: The baud rate is the number of distinct symbols transmitted per second, that is, the number of times per second the signal carrying the communication varies in strength or frequency. If the symbols transmitted have only two states (on or off) then the baud rate is the same as the transmission rate in bits per second. (Adapted from Russ Rowlett's "A Dictionary of Units of Measurement" at http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/)

name: becquerel
description: The activity of a radionuclide decaying at the rate of one spontaneous nuclear transition per second

name: hertz
description: The frequency of a periodic phenomenon of which the period is 1 second.

name: bit per second
description: A unit of transmission speed, equal to one bit per second.

name: cubic metre per time cubic metre
radian
description: The radian is the plane angle between two radii of a circle that cut of, on the circumference,an arc equal in length to the radius.

name: centesimal-second
description: One hundredth of a centesimal-minute.

name: centesimal-minute
description: One hundredth of a centesimal degree (also known as grad, grade or gon)

name: angular degree
description: 1/360 of a full circle = PI /180 radians

name: gon
description: 1/400 of a turn (full circle). Also known as gradian, grad, or grade.

name: angular mil
description: Angle subtended by 1/6400 part of a circle.

name: angular minute
description: 1/60 of an angular degree. ((pi/180) / 60) radians

name: revolution
description: One complete 360 degree rotational cycle.

name: angular second
description: 1/60 of an angular minute. ((pi/180) / 3600) radians

name: angular degree per thirty metre
description: ((pi/180) / 30) radian per metre

name: revolution per cubic foot
description: Outside Energistics

name: angular degree per hour
description: ((pi/180) / 3600) radian per second

name: angular degree per minute
description: ((pi/180) / 60) radian per second

name: angular degree per second
description: (pi/180) radian per second

name: delta Celsius
description: Change in degree Celsius. The degree Celsius and the kelvin are equal in size, so that the numerical value of a temperature difference or temperature interval is the same when expressed in either degrees Celsius or in kelvins (because the offset cancels). For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

name: delta Fahrenheit
description: Change in degrees Fahrenheit. Kelvin=(Fahrenheit + 459.67) x 5/9 so a difference in Fahrenheit temperature cancels out the 459.67 offset. For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

name: delta Rankine
description: Change in degrees Rankine. Rankine = (Celsius + 273.15) x 9/5 so a difference in Fahrenheit temperature cancels out the 273.15 offset. For temperature intervals rather than specific temperatures, 1 deltaF = 1 deltaR = 5/9 deltaC = 5/9 deltaK.

name: delta kelvin
description: Change in kelvin. A zero difference in Kelvin temperature is not the same as being at zero on the Kelvin temperature scale. The degree Celsius and the kelvin are equal in size, so that the numerical value of a temperature difference or temperature interval is the same when expressed in either degrees Celsius or in kelvins.

name: delta Celsius square metre hour per thousand calory
delta Fahrenheit square foot hour per BTU
delta kelvin square metre per kilowatt
delta kelvin square metre per watt
ampere
description: The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross section, and placed 1 metre apart in vacuum, would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2 x 10**-7 newton per metre of length.

name: oersted
description: 1 Oe corresponds to (1000/(12.566370614359172)) A/m. This unit is part of the so-called electromagnetic three-dimensional CGS system and cannot strictly speaking be compared to the corresponding SI unit, which has four dimensions when only mechanical and electric quantities are considered.

name: siemens
description: The electric conductance of a conductor in which a current of 1 A is produced by an electric potential difference of 1 V. Also known as a mho.

name: farad
description: The capacitance of a capacitor between the plates of which there appears a difference of potential of 1 V when it is charged by a quantity of electricity equal to 1 C.

name: coulomb
description: The time integral of electric current, equal to 1 A.s

name: candela
description: The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 X 10**12 hertz and that has a radian intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.

name: lumen
description: The luminous flux emitted in a solid angle of 1 sr by a point source having a uniform intensity of 1 cd.

name: lux
description: The illuminance produced by a luminous flux of 1 lm uniformly distributed over a surface of 1 m2.

name: footcandle
description: A unit of illuminance on a surface that is everywhere one foot from a uniform point source of light of one candle and equal to one lumen per square foot (from www.merriam-webster.com). To convert to Lux, convert the square foot component to square meter (i.e., 1/( 0.3048)**2).

name: lumen second
description: Also known as a talbot.

name: degree kelvin
description: The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.

name: degree Celsius
description: Kelvin minus 273.15

name: degree Fahrenheit
description: Kelvin=(Fahrenheit + 459.67)(5/9)

name: degree Rankine
description: Kelvin=(Rankin)(5/9)

name: metre
description: The metre is the length equal to 1 650 763.73 wavelengths in vacuum of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the levels 2p10 and 5d5 of the krypton-86 atom. In the US, this is called a meter.

name: angstrom
description: The angstrom is widely used by x-ray crystallographers and structural chemists because all chemical bonds lie in the range 1 to 3 angstroms.

name: chain
description: international chain equal to 22 international yards or 66 international feet. From EPSG.

name: British chain [Benoit 1895 A]
description: 66 British foot [Benoit 1895 A]

name: British chain [Benoit 1895 B]
description: 66 British foot [Benoit 1895 B]

name: Clarke chain
description: 66 Clarke foot

name: Indian Chain [1937]
description: 66 Indian foot [1937]

name: British chain [Sears 1922]
description: 66 British foot [Sears 1922]

name: British chain [Sears 1922 truncated]
description: 66 British foot [Sears 1922 truncated]

name: US survey chain
description: 66 US survey feet (exactly). Also called Gunter's chain. From NIST-44.

name: international fathom
description: 6 international foot.

name: foot
description: International foot

name: British foot [Benoit 1895 A]
description: Uses Benoit's 1895 British yard-metre ratio as given by Clark as 0.9143992 metre.s per yard. Used for deriving metric size of ellipsoid in Palestine.

name: British foot [Benoit 1895 B]
description: Uses Benoit's 1895 British yard-metre ratio as given by Bomford as 39.370113 inches per metre. Used in West Malaysian mapping.

name: British foot [1936]
description: For the 1936 retriangulation OSGB defines the relationship of 10 feet of 1796 to the International metre through the logarithmic relationship (10^0.48401603 exactly). 1 ft = 0.3048007491...m. Also used for metric conversions in Ireland.

name: British foot [1865]
description: Uses Clark's estimate of 1853-1865 British foot-metre ratio of 0.9144025 metres per yard. Used in 1962 and 1975 estimates of Indian foot.

name: Clarke foot
description: Assumes Clarke's 1865 ratio of 1 British foot = 0.3047972654 French legal metres applies to the international metre.

name: Gold Coast foot
description: Used in Ghana and some adjacent parts of British west Africa prior to metrication, except for the metrication of projection defining parameters when British foot (Sears 1922) used.

name: indian foot
description: Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). British yard (= 3 British feet) taken to be J.S.Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025 metres.

name: indian foot [1937]
description: Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). British foot taken to be 1895 Benoit value of 12/39.370113m. Rounded to 8 decimal places as 0.30479841. Used from Bangladesh to Vietnam. Previously used in India and Pakistan but superseded.

name: indian foot ]1962]
description: Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). British yard (3 feet) taken to be J.S. Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025m. Rounded to 7 significant figures with a small error as 1 Ind ft=0.3047996m. Used in Pakistan since metrication.

name: indian foot [1975]
description: Indian Foot = 0.99999566 British feet (A.R.Clarke 1865). British yard (3 feet) taken to be J.S. Clark's 1865 value of 0.9144025m. Rounded to 7 significant figures as 1 Ind ft=0.3047995m. Used in India since metrication.

name: British foot [Sears 1922]
description: Uses Sear's 1922 British yard-metre ratio as given by Bomford as 39.370147 inches per metre. Used in East Malaysian and older New Zealand mapping.

name: British foot [Sears 1922 truncated]
description: Uses Sear's 1922 British yard-metre ratio (UoM code 9040) truncated to 6 significant figures; this truncated ratio (0.914398, UoM code 9099) then converted to other imperial units. 3 ftSe(T) = 1 ydSe(T).

name: US survey foot
description: Used in USA.

name: furlong US survey
description: 660 US survey foot (exactly).

name: inch
description: international inch

name: US survey inch
description: 1/12 of US survey foot.

name: link
description: 66/100 international foot. 1/100 international chain.

name: British link [Benoit 1895 A]
description: 66/100 British foot [Benoit 1895 A]

name: British link [Benoit 1895 B]
description: 66/100 British foot [Benoit 1895 B]

name: Clarke link
description: 66/100 Clarke foot

name: British link [Sears 1922]
description: 66/100 British foot [Sears 1922]

name: British link [Sears 1922 truncated]
description: 66/100 British foot (Sears 1922 truncated)

name: US survey link
description: US survey link. Equal to 0.66 US survey foot (exactly).

name: German legal metre
description: Used in Namibia.

name: mile
description: International mile.

name: international nautical mile
description: The nautical mile is a special unit employed for marine and aerial navigation to express distance. The unit was originally chosen, and continues to be used, because one nautical mile on the surface of the Earth subtends approximately one minute of angle at the centre of the Earth, which is convenient when latitude and longitude are measured in degrees and minutes of angle.

name: United Kingdom nautical mile
description: The Imperial (UK) nautical mile, also known as the Admiralty mile, was defined in terms of the knot, such that one nautical mile was exactly 6,080 international feet (1,853.184 m):[6] it was abandoned in 1970[6] and, for legal purposes, old references to the obsolete unit are now converted to 1,853 metres exactly.

name: US survey mile
description: United States survey mile is 5280 feet survey (exactly). From NIST-55.

name: mil
description: One thousandth of an inch.

name: rod US Survey
description: 16.5 US survey feet (exactly)

name: yard
description: International yard.

description: 3 British foot [Benoit 1895 A]

description: 3 British foot [Benoit 1895 B]

name: British yard [Sears 1922]
description: 3 British foot [Sears 1922]

name: British yard [Sears 1922 truncated]
description: 3 British foot [Sears 1922 truncated]

name: US survey yard
description: 3 US survey foot.

name: micrometre
description: Sometimes called a micron.

name: knot
description: The knot is defined as one nautical mile per hour.

cubic foot per second square foot

description: The gal is employed in geodesy and geophysics to express acceleration due to gravity.

name: gravity
description: The standard acceleration due to gravity on Earth.

name: teradarcy-API
description: The API teradarcy is numerically equal to a metre squared.

name: acre
description: US survey acre. Equal to 43,560 square survey foot (exactly). From NIST.

name: barn
description: The barn is a unit of area employed to express cross sections in nuclear physics.

name: hectare
description: Used to express agrarian area.

name: section
description: 640 acres or 1 square US survey mile.

name: darcy
description: The darcy is a unit for expressing the permeability of porous solids, not area (from NIST-SI). One darcy is the permeability of a solid through which one cubic centimeter of fluid, having a viscosity of one centipoise, will flow in one second through a section one centimeter thick and one square centimeter in cross section, if the pressure difference between the two sides of the solid is one atmosphere (from Russ Rowlett's "A Dictionary of Units of Measurement" at http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/). Thus, 1 D=(1 cm3)(1 cP)/((1 s)(1 cm2)(1 atm/cm))=1 cm.cP/(atm.s/cm)=1 cm2.cP/atm.s=(1E-4 m2)(1E-3 Pa.s)/(1.01325E5 Pa.s)=1E-12/1.01325 m2 [exactly]. Also see, Wangen, Magnus (2010) Physical Principles of Sedimentary Basin Analysis (page 12), Cambridge, UK New York: Cambridge University Press, 2010. ISBN 978-0-511-71237-1.

name: darcy-API
description: The darcy is a unit of permeability in fluid flow through a porous medium, having the dimensions of dynamic viscosity multiplied by volume flowrate per unit area and divided by pressure gradient, which simplifies to a dimension of area. A darcy is defined as being exactly equal to 1 um2. A permeability of one darcy will permit a flow of 1 m3/s of fluid of 1 Pa.s viscosity through an area of 1 m2 under a pressure gradient of 10**12 Pa/m.

name: thousand calorie per kilogram delta Celsius
kilowatt hour per kilogram delta Celsius
stokes
description: The stokes is the CGS unit for kinematic viscosity.

name: mole square metre per mole second
pascal second square metre per kilogram
watt square metre delta kelvin per joule delta kelvin
(thousand cubic foot per day) per foot
(thousand cubic metre per day) per metre
(thousand cubic metre per hour) per metre
rad
description: A obsolete unit of absorbed radiation dose. It was originally defined in CGS units in 1953 as the dose causing 100 ergs of energy to be absorbed by one gram of matter. It has been replaced by the gray in most of the world.

name: gray
description: The absorbed dose when the energy per unit mass imparted to matter by ionizing radiation is 1 J/kg

name: sievert
description: The dose equivalent when the absorbed dose of ionizing radiation multiplied by the dimensionless factors Q (quality factor) and N (product of any of the multiplying factors) stipulated by the International Commission on Radiological Protection is 1.0 J/kg.

name: rem
description: A unit of radiation dosage (such as from X rays) applied to humans. Derived from the phrase Roentgen equivalent man, the rem is now defined as the dosage in rads that will cause the same amount of biological injury as one rad of X rays or gamma rays.

name: sievert per second
description: The dose equivalent rate when the absorbed dose per second of ionizing radiation multiplied by the appropriate factors is equivalent to 1 Sievert per second.

name: henry
description: The inductance of a closed circuit in which an electromotive force of 1 V is produced when the electric current in the circuit varies uniformly at a rate of 1 A/s.

name: ohm
description: The electric resistance between two points of a conductor when a constant difference of potential of 1 V, applied between these two points, produces in this conductor a current of 1 A, this conductor not being the source of any electromotive force.

name: weber
description: The magnetic flux which, linking a circuit of one turn, produces in it an electromotive force of 1 V as it is reduced to zero at a uniform rate in 1 s.

name: volt
description: The difference of electric potential between two points of a conductor carrying a constant current of 1 A when the power dissipated between these points is equal to 1 W.

name: joule
description: The work done when the point of application of a force of 1 N is displaced a distance of 1 m in the direction of the force.

name: British thermal unit
description: The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 pound-mass of water 1 degree Fahrenheit. Uses the International Table (IT) calorie which was defined by the Fifth International Conference on the Properties of Steam (London, July 1956) to be exactly 4.1868 J. In order to convert from calorie to BTU, multiply by the conversion from gram to pound-mass and multiply by the conversion from Celsius interval to Fahrenheit interval. That is, 1 calorie= (1e-3/ 0.45359237)*(1/(5/9)) BTU= (.001*9)/(5*0.45359237) BTU= (9/2.26796185e+3) BTU. Given, cal[IT]=4.1868 J, it follows that Btu[IT] = (4.1868*2.26796185e+3)/9 = 1,055.05585262 J.

name: thermochemical British thermal unit
description: The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 pound-mass of water 1 degree Fahrenheit. Based on the thermochemical calorie. In order to convert from calorie to BTU, multiply by the conversion from gram to pound-mass and multiply by the conversion from Celsius interval to Fahrenheit interval. That is, calorie = (1e-3/ 0.45359237)*(1/(5/9)) BTU = (.001*9)/(5*0.45359237) BTU = (9/2.26796185e+3) BTU. Given, cal[th] = 4.184 J, it follows that Btu[th] = (4.184*2.26796185e+3)/9 J = (9.4891523804e+3)/9 J which is approximately 1.0543502644888888888888888888889e+3 J.

name: United Kingdom British thermal unit
description: The legal unit used in the United Kingdom.

name: calorie [International Table]
description: This uses the International Table definition. The amount of heat required at a pressure of one atmosphere to raise the temperature of one gram of water one degree Celsius.

name: calorie
description: This uses the thermochemical definition. The amount of heat required at a pressure of one atmosphere to raise the temperature of one gram of water one degree Celsius.

name: erg
description: An erg is the amount of work done by a force of one dyne exerted for a distance of one centimeter.

name: electronvolt
description: The electronvolt is the kinetic energy acquired by an electron in passing through a potential difference of 1 V in vacuum, 1.602 176 487(40) x 10-19 J. This value of 1 eV is the 2006 CODATA recommended value with the standard uncertainty in the last two digits given in parenthesis. From NIST-SI.

name: quad
description: A quad is a unit of energy equal to 1E+15 (international table) BTU.

name: European Community therm
description: A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU). The therm (EC) is legally defined in the Council Directive of 20 December 1979, Council of the European Communities (now the European Union, EU). It is based on the International Table Btu.

name: United Kingdom therm
description: A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU).

name: United States therm
description: A therm is one hundred thousand BTU (but depends on the definition of BTU). The therm (US) is legally defined in the Federal Register of July 27, 1968. Although the therm (EC), which is based on the International Table Btu, is frequently used by engineers in the United States, the therm (US) is the legal unit used by the U.S. natural gas industry.

name: pound-mass square foot per second squared
thousand calorie
description: thermochemical calorie

name: watt
description: The power that represents a rate of energy transfer of 1 J/s.

name: horsepower
description: The mechanical horsepower, also known as imperial horsepower, of exactly 550 foot pound-force per second.

name: electric-horsepower
description: The horsepower used for electrical machines is defined as exactly 746 W. Outside the United States watts are generally used for electrical power applications.

name: hydraulic-horsepower
description: Also called water horsepower (from NIST-SI). Commonly calculated with the equation HHP=P*Q/1714, where P stands for pressure in pounds per square inch, Q stands for flow rate in gallons per minute, and 1714 is a conversion factor necessary to yield HHP in terms of horsepower (from Schlumberger Oilfield Glossary).

name: metric-horsepower
description: The power to raise a mass of 75 kilograms against the earth's gravitational force over a distance of one metre in one second. Also known as the Pferdestarke (PS), the paardenkracht (pk), the cheval vapeur (CV) and the cavallo vapore (cv).

name: ton-refrigeration
description: A ton of refrigeration is 12,000 (international table) Btu/h.

name: barrel
description: 42 US gallons. 1 barrel of oil (bbl) is defined as exactly 42 US liquid gallons. 1 US liquid gallon is defined as exactly 231 cubic inches (see NIST-130 reference). 1 inch is defined as exactly 0.0254 metres. Therefore, 1 bbl = (42 x 231 x 0.0254**3) m3 = 0.158987294928 m3 exactly. Note that this definition is based in the international inch and NOT the older US survey inch.

name: UK fluid-ounce
description: United Kingdom 1/20 of UK pint. Therefore, 1/160 of UK gallon or (1/160)* 4.54609 cubic decimetres. From UK-1985.

name: US fluid-ounce
description: 1/16 of US pint which is 1/8 of US gallon. Therefore, 1/128 of US gallon.

name: UK gallon
description: United Kingdom Imperial gallon. In Great Britain, a unit of capacity, by the Weights and Measures Act of 1985, exactly "4.54609 cubic decimeters".

name: US gallon
description: The United States liquid gallon is legally defined as 231 cubic inches, and is equal to exactly 3.785411784 litres. Authorized tables, US Code, Title 15, chapter 6, subchapter I, section 205.

name: litre
description: Liquid volume. In the US, this is called a liter. By action of the 12th General Conference on Weights and Measures (1964), the liter is a special name for the cubic decimeter.

name: UK pint
description: There are two pints to one quart

name: US pint
description: There are two pints to one quart

name: UK quart
description: There are four quarts to one gallon.

name: US quart
description: There are four quarts to one gallon.

name: cubic foot
description: The volume of a cube with sides of one foot (0.3048 m) in length

millidarcy square foot per pound-force second
millidarcy square inch per pound-force second

newton
description: That force which, when applied to a body having a mass of 1 kg, gives it an acceleration of 1 m/s2.

name: dyne
description: A unit of force in the centimetre-gram-second system of physical units, equal to the force that would give a free mass of one gram an acceleration of one centimetre per second per second.

name: gram-force
description: The gram-force is equal to a mass of one gram multiplied by the standard acceleration due to gravity on Earth, which is defined as exactly 9.80665 meter per second squared.

name: pound-force
description: The pound-force is equal to the gravitational force exerted on a mass of one avoirdupois pound on the surface of Earth. The exact conversion factor is 4.448 221 615 260 5 E+00 since the standard value of the acceleration due to gravity, gn = 9.806 65 m/s2 exactly, is used to define the kilogram-force: 1 kgf = 9.806 65 E+00 N exactly.

name: ounce-force
description: ounce (avoirdupois)-force

name: poundal
description: A unit of force equal to the force that would give a free mass of one pound an acceleration of one foot per second per second [i.e., "(lbm.ft)/s2"]. Therefore, 1 pdl = 0.138254954376 N exactly. From merriam-webster.com.

name: UK ton-force
description: United Kingdom 2240 lbf.

name: US ton-force
description: 2000 lbf

name: thousand calorie metre per square centimetre
foot pound-force per inch
description: Equivalent to "12 lbf".

name: US ton-force mile per foot
description: Equivalent to "5280 tonf[US]".

name: UK hundredweight

name: US hundredweight
description: 100 lbm. Net or short hundredweight. From NIST-44.

name: gram
description: One thousandth of a kilogram.

name: grain

name: pound-mass
description: International avoirdupois pound.

name: ounce-mass
description: One sixteenth of an International avoirdupois pound (lbm).

name: troy ounce-mass
description: Apothecaries or Troy ounce

name: 94 pound-mass sack
description: A sack with a nominal weight of 94 pound-mass. While the conversion of 94 lbm is exact, the weight of the sack is not exactly 94 lbm.

name: tonne
description: In the US, this is called a metric ton.

name: UK ton-mass
description: Gross or long ton.

name: US ton-mass
description: Net or short ton.

name: kilogram
description: The kilogram is the unit of mass (not force); it is equal to the mass of the international prototype of the kilogram.

name: watt per cubic metre delta kelvin
BTU per hour cubic foot delta Fahrenheit
(BTU per second) per cubic foot delta Fahrenheit
killowatt per cubic metre delta kelvin
watt per square metre delta kelvin
BTU per hour square foot delta Fahrenheit
BTU per hour square foot delta Rankine
BTU per hour square metre delta Celsius
(BTU per second) per square foot delta Fahrenheit
calorie per hour square centimetre delta Celsius
calorie per second square centimetre delta Celsius
joule per second square metre delta Celsius
thousand calorie per hour square metre delta Celsius
kilojoule per hour square metre delta kelvin
kilowatt per square metre delta kelvin
tesla
description: The magnetic flux density of 1 Wb/m2. Alternatively, it is defined as the magnetic flux density that produces on a 1-m length of wire carrying a current of 1A, oriented normal to the flux density, a force of 1 N, magnetic flux density being defined as an axial vector quantity such that the force exerted on an element of current is equal to the vector product of this element and the magnetic flux density.

name: gauss
description: This unit is part of the so-called electromagnetic three-dimensional CGS system and cannot strictly speaking be compared to the corresponding SI unit, which has four dimensions when only mechanical and electric quantities are considered.

name: gram foot per cubic centimetre second
gram metre per cubic centimetre second
ten thousand kilogram per cubic metre
kilogram per metre to the fourth power
gram per centimetre to the fourth power
kilogram per decimetre to the fourth power
pound-mass per foot to the fourth power
pascal second squared per cubic metre
psi squared day per centipoise cubic foot
poise
description: The poise is the CGS unit for viscosity (also called dynamic viscosity).

name: thousand gram-force second per square metre
pascal
description: The pressure or stress of 1 N/m2.

name: technical atmosphere
description: One technical atmosphere equals one kilogram-force per square centimeter (1 at = 1 kgf/cm2). From NIST.

name: standard atmosphere
description: An international reference pressure defined as 101.325 kPa and formerly used as unit of pressure. For practical purposes it has been replaced by the bar which is 100 kPa. The difference of about 1% is not significant for many applications, and is within the error range of common pressure gauges.

name: bar
description: 100 kPa. Since 1982 one bar has been used as the standard pressure for tabulating all thermodynamic data. Prior to 1982 the standard pressure used to be the standard atmosphere, equal to 1.013 25 bar, or 101 325 Pa.

name: centimetre of water at 4 degree Celsius
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: inch of water at 39.2 degree Fahrenheit
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: inch of water at 60 degree Fahrenheit
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: inch of mercury at 32 degree Fahrenheit
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: inch of mercury at 60 degree Fahrenheit
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: millimetres of Mercury at 0 deg C
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: pound-force per square inch
description: Pound-force per square inch. A unit of pressure or of stress based on avoirdupois units. It is the pressure resulting from a force of one pound-force applied to an area of one square inch.

name: torr
description: The torr is defined as 1/760 of one atmosphere, while the atmosphere is defined as 101.325 kPa. Therefore, 1 Torr is equal to 101325/760 Pa (from Wikipedia).

name: micrometre of mercury at 0 degree Celsius
description: NIST-SI gives a limited number of digits of precision and states the following: "Additional digits are not justified because the definitions of the units do not take into account the compressibility of mercury or the change in density caused by the revised practical temperature scale, ITS-90. Similar comments also apply to water manometer pressure units."

name: thousand gram-force metre per square centimetre
millionth of calorie per second square centimetre
gram-mole
description: The mole is the amount (in grams) of substance of a system that contains as many elementary entities as there are atoms in 0.012 kilogram of carbon-12. When the mole is used, the elementary entities must be specified and may be atoms, molecules, ions, electrons, other particles, or specified groups of such particles.

name: pound-mass-mole
description: The amount (in pound-mass) of substance of a system which contains as many elementary entities as there are atoms in 0.012 kilogram of carbon 12. The conversion involves converting pound-mass to kilograms.

name: steradian
description: The steradian is the solid angle that, having its vertex in the center of a circle, cuts of an area of the surface of the sphere equal to that of a square with sides of length equal to the radius of the sphere.

name: second
description: The second is the duration of 9 192 631 770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the cesium-133 atom.

name: julian-year
description: The underlying definition taken from NIST statement that "Julian century = 36 525 d".

name: tropical-year
description: The year as a defined multiple of the second that minimizes time-dependent inaccuracy. Used for expressing very long time intervals both for earth scientists and nuclear physicists alike. Takes into account the non-relativistic estimate of astronomical decrease by 0.530 s per century, for the epoch 2000.0. From "International Union of Geological Sciences" (IUPAC Recommendation 2011).

name: day
description: 24 hours.

name: hour
description: One twenty-fourth of a day or 60 minutes.

name: minute
description: 60 seconds.

name: week
description: A week is seven days.

name: bel
description: A unit of intensity. A bel is the base 10 logarithm of a power or amplitude ratio. In using this unit it is important that the nature of the quantity be specified, and that any reference value used be specified.

name: API gravity unit
description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for gravity of crude petroleum measurements. See the API's Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards (MPMS) chapter 9.1 and chapter 11.1 for information on this concept.

name: API gamma ray unit
description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for gamma ray log measurements.

name: API neutron unit
description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for neutron log measurements.

name: octave
description: The number of octaves between two positive values is the base two logarithm of their ratio.

name: bel per octave
description: The power or amplitude variation that occurs over a doubling of the domain variable.

name: Unitless
description: Outside Energistics

name: Date-time
description: Outside Energistics
